		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../atem.png" alt="ATEM 2006 SI"></a><br><code>atem2006s/paper03</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">ATEM 2006 SI</a> paper:</span><br><i>Formalising Model Transformation Rules for UML/MOF 2</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/CarstenAmelunxen.html">Carsten Amelunxen</a>, <a href="../profile/AndySchürr.html">Andy Schürr</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1049/iet-sen:20070076">10.1049/iet-sen:20070076</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3b.html"><span class="tagM">T3B: Transformation Languages</span></a><ul><li> The paper formalises transformation rules (graph transformations) operating over UML/MOF models, directly addressing transformation-language foundations.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagL">T5D: Formal Methods</span></a><ul><li> Its contribution is a set-theoretic formalisation of transformation semantics for MOF/UML association concepts, i.e., a formal-methods treatment.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> It builds on meta-modelling standards (MOF/OCL) as meta-languages and discusses their integration with transformation formalisms.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> The work is situated in (and motivated by) tool-supported metamodelling frameworks (e.g., MOFLON) that generate executable repositories.
</li></ul></li></ul>
		<clear/>
		<footer/>
